# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(data=data, x=feature, palette="Paired", order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values())

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(100 * p.get_height() / total)  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()      # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(label, (x, y), ha="center", va="center", size=12, xytext=(0, 5), textcoords="offset points")  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

2. Do the users spend more time on the new landing page than the existing landing page? (10 Marks)¶

Perform Visual Analysis¶

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

In [ ]:
H0: time spent on new landing page = time spent on old landing page
Ha: time spent on new landing page > time spent on old landing page

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

2 sample independent T test

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

Standard alpha of .05 for a 95% confidence interval

Step 4: Collect and prepare data¶

In [31]:
histogram_boxplot(df, 'time_spent_on_the_page')

We can see that the dataset is approximately normally distributed. There are 100 tests total (greater than 30 required). We know that this was a random sampling of data with no given standard deviation. Therefore we have fulfilled all the requirements for a t-test.

Continuous data - Yes, the time spent on page is measured on a continuous scale. Normally distributed populations - Yes, we are informed that the populations are assumed to be normal. Independent populations - As we are taking random samples for two different type of users, the two samples are from two independent populations. Unequal population standard deviations - As the sample standard deviations are different (1.8 vs 2.6), the population standard deviations may be assumed to be different. Random sampling from the population - Yes, we are informed that the collected sample is a simple random sample.

Step 5: Calculate the p-value¶

In [149]:
#import the required functions
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

# find the p-value
test_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(newdf['time_spent_on_the_page'], olddf['time_spent_on_the_page'].dropna(), equal_var = False, alternative = 'greater')
print('The p-value is ', p_value)

The p-value is  0.0001392381225166549

Step 6: Compare the p-value with $\alpha$¶

The p - value is 0.00014 which is less than our alpha of .05.

Step 7: Draw inference¶

The p - value is 0.00014 which is less than our alpha of .05, so we must reject our null hypothesis that the means are equal. Therefore the average time spent on the new page is not equal to the average time spent on the old page. In fact the average time spent on the new page is higher than the old page.

A similar approach can be followed to answer the other questions.

3. Is the conversion rate (the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page? (10 Marks)¶

H0: Conversion rate for new landing page = conversion rate for old landing page Ha: Conversion rate for new landing page != conversion rate for old landing page

In [150]:
sns.countplot(data=df, x='landing_page', hue = "converted")
Out[150]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='landing_page', ylabel='count'>

Visually, the proportions of people who converted from the new landing page and the old landing page do not appear to be equal. Further statistical analysis will confirm.

Data requires a 2 proportion Z-test since the population standard deviation is not known. A standard alpha of 0.05 will be used.

Two proportion Z-Test Requirements: Binomally distributed population - Yes, a user either subscribes or does not subscribe. Random sampling from the population - Yes, we are informed that the collected sample is a simple random sample. Can the binomial distribution approximated to normal distribution - Yes. For binary data, CLT works slower than usual. The standard thing is to check whether np and n(1-p) are greater than or equal to 10. Here, n and p refer to the sample size and sample proportion respectively.

np >= 10 n(1-p) >= 10

To fulfill requirements for the two proportion z-test, the above formula must be more or equal to 10. Below is the formulas for the new and old pages.

New Page Converts: Satisfies z-test requirements np = 50 (30/50) = 30 >= 10 n(1-p) = 50 ((50-30)/50) = 20 >= 10

Old Page Converts: Satisfies z-test requirements np = 50 (21/50) = 21 >= 10 n(1-p) = 50 ((50-21)/50) = 29 >= 10

In [140]:
# import the required fuction
from statsmodels.stats.proportion import proportions_ztest

# set the counts of defective items
new_convert = np.array([33, 50])

# set the sample sizes
old_convert = np.array([21, 50])

# find the p-value
test_stat, p_value = proportions_ztest(old_convert, new_convert)
print('The p-value is ' + str(p_value))

The p-value is 4.02101846972016e-06

Since the p-value is much less than our alpha of 0.05 we reject the null hypothesis. Therefore we can conclude that the conversion rate for the new page is not equal to the conversion rate of the old page. The conversion rate is in fact higher for the new page.

Chi squared test for independence to be used to answer this question. Categorical variables - Yes Expected value of the number of sample observations in each level of the variable is at least 5 - Yes, the number of observations in each level is greater than 5. Random sampling from the population - Yes, we are informed that the collected sample is a simple random sample.

H0: language is independent of conversion Ha: language is not independent of conversion

In [137]:
#check if time spent on page follows a normal distribution
# H0 time spent follows normal distribution
# Ha time spent does not follow normal distribution
from scipy import stats

# find the p-value
w, p_value = stats.shapiro(newdf['time_spent_on_the_page']) 
print('The p-value is', p_value)

The p-value is 0.8040016293525696

To test normality the Shapiro-Wilks test is used above. H0: Time spent on page follows a normal distribution Ha: Time spent on page does not follow a normal distribution.

p-value is greater than 0.05, so we cannot reject our null hypothesis. The Time Spent on page dataset is normally distributed.

To test if the variances are equal we use Levene's Test. H0: all variances are equal Ha: at least one variance is different

In [138]:

                                   newdf['time_spent_on_the_page'][newdf['language_preferred']=="Spanish"], 
                                   newdf['time_spent_on_the_page'][newdf['language_preferred']=="French"])
# find the p-value
print('The p-value is', p_value)

The p-value is 0.46711357711340173

p-value is greater than 0.05 so we cannot reject the null hypothesis. All variances are equal for this dataset.

The populations are normally distributed - Yes, the normality assumption is verified using the Shapiro-Wilks test. Samples are independent simple random samples - Yes, we are informed that the collected sample is a simple random sample. Population variances are equal - Yes, the homogeneity of variance assumption is verified using the Levene's test.

p-value is greater than 0.05 so we cannot reject the null hypothesis. The time spent on the new landing page is not significantly different for different language users.

Conclusion and Business Recommendations¶

Question 2 shows us The p - value is less than our alpha of .05 so we must reject our null hypothesis that the means are equal. Therefore the average time spent on the new page is not equal to the average time spent on the old page. In fact time spent on the new page is more than time spent on the old page.

Question 3 revealed that the p-value is much less than our alpha of 0.05 we reject the null hypothesis. Therefore we can conclude that the conversion rate for the new page is not equal to the conversion rate of the old page. The conversion rate is in fact higher for the new page.

Question 4 demonstrated the p-value is greater than our alpha of 0.05, so we cannot reject our null hypothesis. Therefore language is independent of conversion.

Question 5 showed that the p-value is greater than 0.05 so we cannot reject the null hypothesis. The time spent on the new landing page is not significantly different for different language users. It is

From the statistical analysis we can see that the new landing page is more successful at gaining new subscriptions and keeping users on the page for longer. It seems in the best interest of the company if the new landing page is launched to replace the old landing page. Language does not have any effect on subscriptions or use on the new landing page from the previous statistical calculations.

In short, the new landing page is statistically proven to be more effective at gaining a higher percentage of subscriptions.
